WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.719 --> 00:00:05.259
So in this tutorial we're going to be going
over how to add PBR textures to absolutely

00:00:05.259 --> 00:00:06.319
any model in blender.

00:00:06.319 --> 00:00:10.200
And of course before we do this we need to
make sure that we have some of these textures

00:00:10.200 --> 00:00:11.200
downloaded.

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:15.580
So in my case I'm going to get them from my
own website which is cgmatter.com.

00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:18.769
You can get textures from absolutely anywhere,
in this case I'm just going to be using my

00:00:18.769 --> 00:00:19.769
own.

00:00:19.769 --> 00:00:21.599
I'm going to use this right here.

00:00:21.599 --> 00:00:25.060
And then we get the seamless textures for
free, at least on this website.

00:00:25.060 --> 00:00:29.489
And I'm going to download 2k version and then
once you do this it's going to eventually

00:00:29.489 --> 00:00:30.849
start downloading.

00:00:30.849 --> 00:00:32.730
Of course mine is already downloaded here.

00:00:32.730 --> 00:00:38.560
You're going to get an ambient occlusion basecolor
height metallic normal and roughness maps.

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:42.610
And we want to know how to add these into
a material in blender.

00:00:42.610 --> 00:00:47.440
So we can actually close this right here.So
how do we add this to our cube?

00:00:47.440 --> 00:00:51.830
So we're going to start off my going to shading
and we want to have a HDRI so we have some

00:00:51.830 --> 00:00:52.830
lighting going on.

00:00:52.830 --> 00:00:54.580
So I'm going to change this to world.

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:58.400
And I already made a tutorial on how to add
a HDRI, so I'm going to do it quickly.

00:00:58.400 --> 00:00:59.400
But I'll try to explain it.

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:01.440
We're going to close this.

00:01:01.440 --> 00:01:05.100
We're going to click shift a which is going
to let us add a texture.

00:01:05.100 --> 00:01:06.350
Environment texture.

00:01:06.350 --> 00:01:09.470
We're going to connect this to the surface
of the world.

00:01:09.470 --> 00:01:12.640
And then we're going to open any HDRI you
already have downloaded.

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:16.320
In this case I'll be using this one and then
here we go.

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:19.110
Now we actually want to work on the material
of the cube.

00:01:19.110 --> 00:01:20.490
So how do we do that?

00:01:20.490 --> 00:01:22.960
So what you want to do is go over to object.

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:28.460
And by default you should already have a principled
bsdf with an output setup.

00:01:28.460 --> 00:01:31.110
If you don't you can close whatever material
you have.

00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:33.010
Click new and it will show up.

00:01:33.010 --> 00:01:36.880
If for some reason you don't like that you
can just hit shift a.

00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:41.630
Go to shader and then add a principle bsdf
shader right here.

00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:43.190
And then you have the same thing.

00:01:43.190 --> 00:01:45.420
Connect those and we're back to square one.

00:01:45.420 --> 00:01:48.220
Ok so how do we connect all these maps?

00:01:48.220 --> 00:01:50.740
So we're going to go in some kind of order.

00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:55.110
So first of all ambient occlusion, this one
is special because we actually do not need

00:01:55.110 --> 00:01:56.119
it in blender.

00:01:56.119 --> 00:02:00.840
This is pretty much calculated on render in
cycles and in eevee.

00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:03.490
This is more for game engines so we don't
actually use this.

00:02:03.490 --> 00:02:05.510
So we're going to start with basecolor.

00:02:05.510 --> 00:02:07.229
We're just going to drag this in.

00:02:07.229 --> 00:02:10.899
And of course basecolor is going to be the
color of the cube.

00:02:10.899 --> 00:02:14.610
So we're going to take this color and connect
it to basecolor.

00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:17.230
And there we go, it's showing up.

00:02:17.230 --> 00:02:20.280
Next what we want to do is we're going to
go to metallic.

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:22.569
We're going to drag this in.

00:02:22.569 --> 00:02:26.420
And then one special thing about metallic
is you don't want to necessarily take this

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:31.120
and just connect it to metallic because you
need to make sure his right here, this color,

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:33.599
is set to non-color data.

00:02:33.599 --> 00:02:38.940
And that's because a metallic map is basically
supposed to be values between 0 and 1.

00:02:38.940 --> 00:02:41.370
Not necessarily the color data.

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:44.040
Ok so we have that.

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:47.170
Next we're going to go over to roughness which
same business.

00:02:47.170 --> 00:02:48.319
We're going to take it.

00:02:48.319 --> 00:02:50.560
We're going to connect it to roughness.

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:56.950
But we want to set this color to non-color
data because we want values between 0 and

00:02:56.950 --> 00:02:58.010
1.

00:02:58.010 --> 00:03:01.370
Next we have, let's see, we can do normal
and height.

00:03:01.370 --> 00:03:03.720
And for these we kind of combine them in a
special way.

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:04.720
I'll show you how.

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:06.020
So we're going to take our normal map.

00:03:06.020 --> 00:03:07.960
Bring it in here.

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:12.450
We're going to take our height map, some people
call it a displacement map.

00:03:12.450 --> 00:03:14.840
These things are generally the same.

00:03:14.840 --> 00:03:16.290
And then we put this right here.

00:03:16.290 --> 00:03:20.400
So we have these two maps and what I'm going
to do is I'm going to set both of these to

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:21.739
non-color data.

00:03:21.739 --> 00:03:24.780
This is very important, if you don't do this
it's going to look very bizarre.

00:03:24.780 --> 00:03:27.400
Ok, now what we need is a bump node.

00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:31.750
So just click shift a and in here you can
type bump or you can try to find it.

00:03:31.750 --> 00:03:34.879
I think it's in vector, bump.

00:03:34.879 --> 00:03:38.129
And then in this bump we see we have a normal
input and a height input.

00:03:38.129 --> 00:03:39.760
So it's pretty obvious what you do.

00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:42.650
Take this height, no this one is the height.

00:03:42.650 --> 00:03:44.790
Take the height and put it in height.

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:49.370
And note that this normal input is purple
while this one is yellow.

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:51.489
This is indicating that this is just an image.

00:03:51.489 --> 00:03:53.849
It's a texture, it's not a normal map.

00:03:53.849 --> 00:03:55.709
So what we have to do is convert it.

00:03:55.709 --> 00:04:02.440
So shift a and here you can either type normal
map or go to vector and add a normal map node.

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:04.190
We're going to take this, connect it.

00:04:04.190 --> 00:04:05.870
So now we have a normal map.

00:04:05.870 --> 00:04:08.620
And then we're going to connect this in here.

00:04:08.620 --> 00:04:12.849
And then finally we take this bump node, connect
it into our normal socket.

00:04:12.849 --> 00:04:14.790
Ok, it's going to take a second.

00:04:14.790 --> 00:04:18.100
And already it's looking much more 3D.

00:04:18.100 --> 00:04:21.370
Now lets say that these brick are too big.

00:04:21.370 --> 00:04:22.840
You want them to tile smaller.

00:04:22.840 --> 00:04:24.680
So you want more tiles.

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:26.169
So the question is how do you do this?

00:04:26.169 --> 00:04:29.710
What we're going to do is take each of our
image inputs and we're going to line them

00:04:29.710 --> 00:04:31.190
up.

00:04:31.190 --> 00:04:33.729
Take these three, shift them over.

00:04:33.729 --> 00:04:36.650
Woops I accidentally shifted over this one
too.

00:04:36.650 --> 00:04:41.150
And what we want to do is basically change
the mapping so that we add twice as much or

00:04:41.150 --> 00:04:43.180
three times as many bricks here.

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:45.720
So what we want to do, shift a.

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:47.410
And then you want to add a couple things.

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:49.500
You're going to start off with a mapping node.

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:52.240
So go to vector, mapping.

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:55.780
And then you're going to connect this vector
to each of these.

00:04:55.780 --> 00:04:58.240
So that's going to be a couple of connections.

00:04:58.240 --> 00:05:00.840
Let me close that.

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:02.840
Connect this here.

00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:09.500
A bit of work but overall less work then making
a shader from scratch.

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:11.160
So we're going to connect all of these.

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:15.190
Ok so now we have this mapping node and we're
going to want to change the size.

00:05:15.190 --> 00:05:18.690
But before we do that we need to add a coordinate
input.

00:05:18.690 --> 00:05:20.340
So you're going to click shift a.

00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:24.530
And then I believe it's in input, texture
coordinates.

00:05:24.530 --> 00:05:27.560
And then it depends on what coordinates you're
using.

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:29.560
Most of the time you use UV maps.

00:05:29.560 --> 00:05:31.979
So we're going to be using a UV map.

00:05:31.979 --> 00:05:37.330
There are cases where you use other things
but in this case, our cube if you go to UV

00:05:37.330 --> 00:05:38.710
editing.

00:05:38.710 --> 00:05:43.050
You see that it's already UV mapped so that's
why we're using that.

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:48.740
So now we have this coordinate going into
this mapping which is going into all our textures

00:05:48.740 --> 00:05:51.030
which are doing their respective things.

00:05:51.030 --> 00:05:52.990
So how do we actually affect this?

00:05:52.990 --> 00:05:56.160
Well you just drag the scale and you see what
it's doing already.

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:59.750
So lets double it in both directions.

00:05:59.750 --> 00:06:00.750
There we go.

00:06:00.750 --> 00:06:02.229
And I don't actually know what the z does.

00:06:02.229 --> 00:06:03.669
I think it's irrelevant to this case.

00:06:03.669 --> 00:06:07.170
Ya it doesn't do anything, at least I don't
think it does anything.

00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:08.520
Let's see.

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:10.620
Ya, doesn't do anything.

00:06:10.620 --> 00:06:14.270
If we want even more tiles again this is seamless
so it's going to work out.

00:06:14.270 --> 00:06:15.900
We can have triple as many.

00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:18.680
So three times and then this is how you do
it.

00:06:18.680 --> 00:06:23.389
And of course we have a seam along here because
there is a seam in our UV map here.

00:06:23.389 --> 00:06:26.730
But generally this is how you do it.

00:06:26.730 --> 00:06:30.680
And just to see the full effects, by the way
we've been using eevee this whole time.

00:06:30.680 --> 00:06:34.430
But again the setup for eevee is identical
to that of cycles.

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:38.970
We just switch this over to cycles and you
see that everything is working.

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:40.910
Change this to GPU compute.

00:06:40.910 --> 00:06:43.750
Goes a bit faster on my computer.

00:06:43.750 --> 00:06:46.310
And you see it's already working here.

00:06:46.310 --> 00:06:50.240
And if you want to see this lighting change
around so you can really see the depth in

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:51.960
the bricks and all this.

00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:55.389
Go back to world and we're going to do a similar
setup here.

00:06:55.389 --> 00:06:58.270
So with our HDRI we're going to add a mapping.

00:06:58.270 --> 00:07:02.340
This time I'm just going to type it in.

00:07:02.340 --> 00:07:05.270
Add our mapping.

00:07:05.270 --> 00:07:07.490
And then we're going to add some coordinates.

00:07:07.490 --> 00:07:09.570
So input, texture coordinates.

00:07:09.570 --> 00:07:12.310
And in this case I'm pretty sure we use generated
not UV.

00:07:12.310 --> 00:07:15.610
So that's an instance where you use generated.

00:07:15.610 --> 00:07:17.919
And this is actually a case where we use our
z input.

00:07:17.919 --> 00:07:22.860
I can like rotate this like that and then
you see the lighting is changing.

00:07:22.860 --> 00:07:24.680
Takes a bit because it's cycles.

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:27.950
We can actually just go back to eevee like
that.

00:07:27.950 --> 00:07:30.310
And then we can a more fluid motion.

00:07:30.310 --> 00:07:33.350
And by the way as I said we don't need ambient
occlusion maps.

00:07:33.350 --> 00:07:38.410
Cycles obviously does it but eevee you just
click ambient occlusion.

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:44.600
And you see these gaps in-between the bricks
automatically get their ambient occlusion.

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:47.479
This is how you do PBR in blender.

00:07:47.479 --> 00:07:52.250
So again we do not, we do not use ambient
occlusion unless you want to do some like

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:53.860
very weird stylistic thing.

00:07:53.860 --> 00:07:57.360
It's not physically accurate you don't want
to use it.

00:07:57.360 --> 00:07:59.060
Basecolor goes in basecolor.

00:07:59.060 --> 00:08:00.820
Let's see.

00:08:00.820 --> 00:08:03.660
Metallic goes in metallic but set this to
non-color.

00:08:03.660 --> 00:08:05.900
Roughness and roughness set it to non-color.

00:08:05.900 --> 00:08:10.319
You take your normal and height and change
your normal to a normal map and then feed

00:08:10.319 --> 00:08:12.030
them both into a bump.

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:17.729
And then put this in our normal socket and
then we can always change our tiling using

00:08:17.729 --> 00:08:18.740
these.

00:08:18.740 --> 00:08:21.500
And then one final note is with this bump
map.

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:27.900
You can actually control how much this thing
is at least looks like it's extruding.

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:32.789
So we can change the strength here and you
can see how that works.

00:08:32.789 --> 00:08:38.860
Generally you want to keep this at one unless
your textures aren't pre-calibrated to already

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:40.800
be exactly what you want.

00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:46.610
So again, I used textures from cgmatter.com
textures for free if you want them there.

00:08:46.610 --> 00:08:52.459
I mean it's an advertisement for my own site
but it's free so consider it maybe.

00:08:52.459 --> 00:08:53.550
So hopefully this helped.

00:08:53.550 --> 00:08:55.170
Thank you for watching.

00:08:55.170 --> 00:08:56.029
And hope you learned something.

